{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"nvidiaTeslaT4","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":13973040,"datasetId":8908164,"databundleVersionId":14747316},{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":15157046,"datasetId":9705758,"databundleVersionId":16047893}],"dockerImageVersionId":31287,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":true}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Person Search on PRW Dataset\n## Machine Learning for Computer Vision, University of Bologna, A.Y. 2025-2026\n\n|       |      |\n|-------|-------|\n| **Full Name** | `Luwam Major Kefali` |\n| **Email** | `luwammajor.kefali@studio.unibo.it` |\n\n**Task:** Implement a Person Search model (joint pedestrian detection + person re-identification) on the PRW dataset.\n\n**Platform:** Kaggle, 2x T4 GPUs. Training runs via `torchrun` with DistributedDataParallel.\n\n**How to run:** Set `TRAINING_MODE = False` to skip training and load pre-trained weights for evaluation. Set `True` to retrain via DDP (approximately 2 hours on 2x T4). ","metadata":{"_uuid":"cfdcae7f-b561-41d5-b8d9-bc30a88b1b0d","_cell_guid":"7bd2b0d1-8754-4891-aa04-30a90c6c61c4","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 1. Introduction\n\nPerson Search combines pedestrian detection and person re-identification into a single end-to-end pipeline. Unlike classical Re-ID, where bounding boxes are given by a perfect detector, Person Search operates on raw scene images. The model must locate all persons and identify the target simultaneously, which makes it closer to a real surveillance scenario, for example finding a missing person in a crowded area (Zheng et al., CVPR 2017).\n\nThe main advantage of an end-to-end approach over a two-stage pipeline (detect, then re-identify separately) is that the backbone features are shared. The detector and the Re-ID branch can co-adapt: the backbone learns representations that are good for both localization and discrimination. Errors from the detector no longer propagate blindly to the Re-ID module since the two tasks are trained jointly (Xiao et al., CVPR 2017).\n\nIn this project I build an end-to-end model based on Faster R-CNN with an added Re-ID head trained using OIM loss (Online Instance Matching). I run two ablation studies to verify the design choices: swapping ResNet-50 for ResNet-18 (testing backbone capacity), and replacing OIM with batch-hard triplet loss (testing the Re-ID objective).\n\nTraining uses DistributedDataParallel across 2 T4 GPUs (Kaggle), with Weights & Biases for experiment tracking.","metadata":{"_uuid":"1e0f0b02-363b-45ec-bea6-61291c33c449","_cell_guid":"1aceeaa7-7702-425d-91d9-f55379bf82a7","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import os\n\n# check scripts\nscripts_path = \"/kaggle/input/prw-person-search-scripts\"\nprint(\"Scripts:\", os.listdir(scripts_path))\n\n# check dataset\nfor root, dirs, files in os.walk(\"/kaggle/input\"):\n    depth = root.replace(\"/kaggle/input\", \"\").count(os.sep)\n    if depth < 2:\n        print(f\"{root}: {len(files)} files, {len(dirs)} dirs\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-12T20:57:46.487299Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-12T20:57:46.487914Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-12T20:57:46.495116Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-12T20:57:46.487880Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-12T20:57:46.494176Z"}},"outputs":[{"traceback":["\u001b[0;31m---------------------------------------------------------------------------\u001b[0m","\u001b[0;31mFileNotFoundError\u001b[0m                         Traceback (most recent call last)","\u001b[0;32m/tmp/ipykernel_55/2038365984.py\u001b[0m in \u001b[0;36m<cell line: 0>\u001b[0;34m()\u001b[0m\n\u001b[1;32m      3\u001b[0m \u001b[0;31m# check scripts\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\n\u001b[1;32m      4\u001b[0m \u001b[0mscripts_path\u001b[0m \u001b[0;34m=\u001b[0m \u001b[0;34m\"/kaggle/input/prw-person-search-scripts\"\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\n\u001b[0;32m----> 5\u001b[0;31m \u001b[0mprint\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m(\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\"Scripts:\"\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m,\u001b[0m \u001b[0mos\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m.\u001b[0m\u001b[0mlistdir\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m(\u001b[0m\u001b[0mscripts_path\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m)\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m)\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\n\u001b[0m\u001b[1;32m      6\u001b[0m \u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\n\u001b[1;32m      7\u001b[0m \u001b[0;31m# check dataset\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0;34m\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\n","\u001b[0;31mFileNotFoundError\u001b[0m: [Errno 2] No such file or directory: '/kaggle/input/prw-person-search-scripts'"],"ename":"FileNotFoundError","evalue":"[Errno 2] No such file or directory: '/kaggle/input/prw-person-search-scripts'","output_type":"error"}],"execution_count":7},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import shutil, glob, os\n\ninput_dirs = [\n    \"/kaggle/input/prw-person-search-scripts\",\n    \"/kaggle/input/prw-person-search-weights\",\n]\nfor src_dir in input_dirs:\n    if os.path.exists(src_dir):\n        for f in glob.glob(os.path.join(src_dir, \"*\")):\n            shutil.copy(f, \".\")\n        print(f\"Copied from {src_dir}\")\n    else:\n        print(f\"Not found (skipping): {src_dir}\")\n\nprint(\"Working dir:\", sorted([f for f in os.listdir(\".\")\n                               if not f.startswith(\"__\")]))\n\n# install packages\nimport subprocess, sys\nfor p in [\"kagglehub\", \"scipy\", \"scikit-learn\", \"matplotlib\", \"tqdm\", \"wandb\"]:\n    subprocess.run([sys.executable, \"-m\", \"pip\", \"install\", \"-q\", p], check=False)\n\nprint(\"Setup complete\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"e260ba7d-c6b7-48b2-8922-3051725be9f1","_cell_guid":"cf6aa61c-4205-41d0-bb21-5bb9c6f44862","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import os, os.path as osp, random, warnings\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport matplotlib.patches as patches\nfrom PIL import Image\nfrom collections import Counter\n\nimport torch\nimport torchvision\nimport torchvision.transforms as T\n\n# our modules \nfrom dataset import PRWGalleryDataset, PRWQueryDataset\nfrom models import build_model\nfrom eval_utils import (extract_gallery_features, extract_query_features,\n                        eval_search_prw, collate_fn)\n\nwarnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\")\ntorch.manual_seed(42)\nrandom.seed(42)\nnp.random.seed(42)\n\nDEVICE = torch.device(\"cuda\" if torch.cuda.is_available() else \"cpu\")\nprint(f\"Device: {DEVICE}\")\nprint(f\"GPUs available: {torch.cuda.device_count()}\")\nprint(f\"PyTorch {torch.__version__}, torchvision {torchvision.__version__}\")\n\n# config\nTRAINING_MODE   = False\nREID_DIM        = 256\nNUM_TRAIN_PIDS  = 482\nDET_THRESH      = 0.5\nDATASET_ROOT    = None   # set after donwload","metadata":{"_uuid":"f5b902f3-6998-49d2-a50d-43f35cf9ca73","_cell_guid":"83128489-39fa-4c73-81f2-d461a6975c18","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import kagglehub\n\npath = kagglehub.dataset_download(\n    \"edoardomerli/prw-person-re-identification-in-the-wild\")\nprint(\"Downloaded to:\", path)\n\nfor root_candidate, dirs, files in os.walk(path):\n    if \"frame_train.mat\" in files:\n        DATASET_ROOT = root_candidate\n        break\n\nassert DATASET_ROOT is not None, \"Could not find PRW root\"\nprint(f\"PRW root: {DATASET_ROOT}\")\nprint(\"Contents:\", sorted(os.listdir(DATASET_ROOT)))","metadata":{"_uuid":"7661ef38-73a4-4915-81b0-b3d5e368c2dd","_cell_guid":"e04e0345-a618-408d-9c29-015c03ab9e31","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 2. Dataset: PRW\n\nThe PRW dataset (Zheng et al., CVPR 2017) contains 11,816 frames from 6 cameras with 43,110 annotated pedestrian bounding boxes. Of these, 34,304 are assigned to one of 932 identities, while the rest are labeled \"ambiguous\" (ID = -2). There are 2,057 query bounding boxes for evaluation.\n\n| Split | Frames | IDs | Total BBoxes | Labeled | Unlabeled |\n|-------|--------|-----|-------------|---------|-----------|\n| Train | 5,134  | 482 | 16,243      | 13,416  | 2,827     |\n| Val   | 570    | 482 | 1,805       | 1,491   | 314       |\n| Test  | 6,112  | 450 | 25,062      | 19,127  | 5,935     |\n\nA small number of IDs appear in both train and test frames, but the query IDs (the ones we evaluate on) are exclusive to the test set, so there is no identity leakage during evaluation.","metadata":{"_uuid":"46531dce-1de1-4cdb-ad4c-e535d45ce234","_cell_guid":"dc61ecb9-3695-484f-a4f0-db27e32ada0c","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"train_dataset = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"train\")\nval_dataset   = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"val\")\ntest_dataset  = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"test\")\nquery_dataset = PRWQueryDataset(DATASET_ROOT)\n\nprint(f\"Train frames : {len(train_dataset):,}\")\nprint(f\"Val   frames : {len(val_dataset):,}\")\nprint(f\"Test  frames : {len(test_dataset):,}\")\nprint(f\"Queries      : {len(query_dataset):,}\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"48735f4f-9099-41be-b0b5-308fa6327371","_cell_guid":"56774745-d8d8-49a1-8779-bf0a0dc3e721","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Data Exploration\n\nBefore building the model, I inspect the data to understand its characteristics. Specifically: how often each identity appears (are some IDs rare?), the distribution of bounding box heights (what scale variation do we have?), and aspect ratios (are the boxes roughly consistent?). This is useful for sanity checking and can inform choices like anchor sizes.","metadata":{"_uuid":"83a3a0a3-7415-4f61-8638-06182fdb4358","_cell_guid":"a32c66d1-3969-4d59-85b1-b39da7034580","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"all_pids, all_widths, all_heights = [], [], []\nfor ann in train_dataset.annotations:\n    for b, p in zip(ann[\"boxes\"], ann[\"pids\"]):\n        if p > 0:\n            all_pids.append(p)\n            all_widths.append(b[2] - b[0])\n            all_heights.append(b[3] - b[1])\n\npid_counts = Counter(all_pids)\n\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 4))\n\naxes[0].hist(list(pid_counts.values()), bins=40, color=\"#4C72B0\", edgecolor=\"white\")\naxes[0].set_title(\"Appearances per Identity (Train)\")\naxes[0].set_xlabel(\"# appearances\")\naxes[0].set_ylabel(\"# identities\")\n\naxes[1].hist(all_heights, bins=50, color=\"#DD8452\", edgecolor=\"white\")\naxes[1].set_title(\"Bounding Box Heights (px)\")\naxes[1].set_xlabel(\"height (px)\")\n\nratios = np.array(all_heights) / np.array(all_widths)\naxes[2].hist(ratios, bins=50, color=\"#55A868\", edgecolor=\"white\")\naxes[2].set_title(\"Aspect Ratios (h/w)\")\naxes[2].set_xlabel(\"aspect ratio\")\n\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig(\"eda_statistics.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()\n\nprint(f\"Median box height:  {np.median(all_heights):.1f} px\")\nprint(f\"Median aspect ratio: {np.median(ratios):.2f}\")\nprint(f\"Unique train IDs:   {len(pid_counts)}\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"9a206969-72dc-4b68-be80-f7e474ef20bf","_cell_guid":"c0373677-b4a7-40b7-989c-378fd0fbe4e9","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def show_scene(dataset, idx, title=\"\"):\n    ann = dataset.annotations[idx]\n    img = np.array(Image.open(\n        osp.join(dataset.img_prefix, ann[\"img_name\"])).convert(\"RGB\"))\n    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(12, 5))\n    ax.imshow(img)\n    cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap(\"tab20\", 30)\n    for box, pid in zip(ann[\"boxes\"], ann[\"pids\"]):\n        x1, y1, x2, y2 = box\n        color = cmap(pid % 20) if pid > 0 else \"gray\"\n        rect = patches.Rectangle((x1, y1), x2 - x1, y2 - y1,\n                                  linewidth=2, edgecolor=color, facecolor=\"none\")\n        ax.add_patch(rect)\n        lbl = str(pid) if pid > 0 else \"?\"\n        ax.text(x1, y1 - 4, lbl, color=color, fontsize=7,\n                fontweight=\"bold\", bbox=dict(fc=\"white\", alpha=0.4, pad=1))\n    ax.set_title(title or ann[\"img_name\"])\n    ax.axis(\"off\")\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.show()\n\nfor i in [0, 50, 200]:\n    show_scene(train_dataset, i, title=f\"Train sample #{i}\")\n\n# query crops\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 8, figsize=(20, 5))\nfor i, ax in enumerate(axes):\n    ann = query_dataset.annotations[i]\n    img = Image.open(osp.join(query_dataset.query_dir, ann[\"img_name\"])).convert(\"RGB\")\n    ax.imshow(img)\n    ax.set_title(f\"PID {ann['pids']}\\nCam {ann['cam_id']}\", fontsize=9)\n    ax.axis(\"off\")\nplt.suptitle(\"Sample Query Crops\", fontsize=13, y=1.02)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig(\"query_samples.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()","metadata":{"_uuid":"f5bcf0f2-99ca-4fea-a21a-f50330b35f38","_cell_guid":"d313a0ca-a485-4eb2-8c17-cf127167a700","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. Model Architecture\n\nThe code for the model, loss functions, and evaluation is in separate Python scripts (`models.py`, `losses.py`, `eval_utils.py`) for readability and because the DDP training script (`train_ddp.py`) needs to import them too.\n\nThe architecture is a Faster R-CNN with an additional Re-ID branch:\n\n1. **Backbone (ResNet + FPN):** extracts multi-scale features from the input.\n2. **RPN:** generates region proposals likely to contain pedestrians.\n3. **RoI Align:** crops and resizes features per proposal into 7x7 maps.\n4. **Box Head (TwoMLPHead):** maps the pooled features to a 1024-d vector.\n5. **Detection Head:** classifies (person vs. background) and refines boxes.\n6. **Re-ID Head:** projects the same 1024-d vector to a 256-d L2-normalized embedding.\n\nDuring training, the joint loss is:\n\n$$\\mathcal{L} = \\mathcal{L}_{cls} + \\mathcal{L}_{reg} + \\lambda \\cdot \\mathcal{L}_{reid}$$\n\nwhere $\\mathcal{L}_{reid}$ is either OIM or triplet loss, and $\\lambda = 0.5$.\n\n**OIM loss** (Xiao et al., CVPR 2017) maintains a lookup table of identity prototypes updated via exponential moving average, plus a circular queue for unlabeled samples. Each embedding is compared to all entries via scaled cosine similarity. This lets the model see all 482 training identities at every step, regardless of batch composition, which is critical when batch sizes are small.\n\n**Triplet loss** (Hermans et al., 2017) uses batch-hard mining: for each anchor, it selects the hardest positive and hardest negative within the batch. The limitation is that with 2 images per GPU, only a few IDs are present per step.\n\nThe full model code is in `models.py`, losses in `losses.py`.","metadata":{"_uuid":"6eb738d5-2dc8-4df6-b1e0-483ea3cb4fe9","_cell_guid":"643904a0-a364-4a2a-a5b6-40cd5b9fff7f","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Training with DDP\n\nTraining uses PyTorch's `DistributedDataParallel` across Kaggle's 2 T4 GPUs, launched via `torchrun`. The key differences from single-GPU training:\n\n- **Process spawning:** `torchrun` launches one process per GPU. Each process initializes its own model replica.\n- **DistributedSampler:** the dataset is automatically partitioned so each GPU sees a different subset of images per epoch. `sampler.set_epoch(epoch)` is called each epoch to reshuffle.\n- **Gradient synchronization:** DDP automatically averages gradients across GPUs after each backward pass, so the model parameters stay in sync.\n- **Logging:** only rank 0 prints, logs to wandb, and saves checkpoints, to avoid duplicate output.\n\nThe effective batch size is `batch_size_per_gpu * num_gpus`. With 2 images per GPU and 2 GPUs, the effective batch is 4, which is twice what a single T4 can handle.\n\nI train three variants:\n1. **Baseline:** ResNet-50 + OIM\n2. **Ablation A:** ResNet-18 + OIM (testing backbone depth)\n3. **Ablation B:** ResNet-50 + Triplet (testing loss function)\n\nAll training metrics are logged to Weights & Biases.","metadata":{"_uuid":"86bf00a6-b27d-4500-94f9-8b53ecd07e08","_cell_guid":"e556e7e0-7559-4000-b7bb-48b2863d7be4","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"if TRAINING_MODE:\n    # make sure wandb is configured\n    # (set your API key as a Kaggle secret named WANDB_API_KEY,\n    #  or run wandb.login() interactively before this cell)\n    import wandb\n    wandb.login()\n\n    # baseline: resnet50 + OIM\n    os.system(\n        \"torchrun --nproc_per_node=2 train_ddp.py \"\n        \"--backbone resnet50 --loss oim --tag baseline \"\n        \"--epochs 20 --batch_size 2 --lr 0.003\"\n    )\n\n    # ablation A: resnet18 + OIM\n    os.system(\n        \"torchrun --nproc_per_node=2 train_ddp.py \"\n        \"--backbone resnet18 --loss oim --tag resnet18 \"\n        \"--epochs 20 --batch_size 2 --lr 0.003\"\n    )\n\n    # ablation B: resnet50 + triplet\n    os.system(\n        \"torchrun --nproc_per_node=2 train_ddp.py \"\n        \"--backbone resnet50 --loss triplet --tag triplet \"\n        \"--epochs 20 --batch_size 2 --lr 0.003\"\n    )\n\n    print(\"All training runs complete\")\nelse:\n    print(\"Training skipped (TRAINING_MODE=False). Loading weights below.\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"7f414742-af73-4faf-872e-66da7dabc2d7","_cell_guid":"2fb62431-9e56-4ed9-b310-29711a907391","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def load_model(backbone_name, loss_type, weight_path, device):\n    model = build_model(backbone_name=backbone_name, loss_type=loss_type,\n                        pretrained=False).to(device)\n    ckpt = torch.load(weight_path, map_location=device, weights_only=False)\n    model.load_state_dict(ckpt[\"model\"])\n    model.eval()\n    return model, ckpt.get(\"loss_log\", [])\n\n\nmodel_baseline, log_baseline = load_model(\n    \"resnet50\", \"oim\", \"weights_baseline.pt\", DEVICE)\nmodel_resnet18, log_resnet18 = load_model(\n    \"resnet18\", \"oim\", \"weights_resnet18.pt\", DEVICE)\nmodel_triplet, log_triplet = load_model(\n    \"resnet50\", \"triplet\", \"weights_triplet.pt\", DEVICE)\n\nprint(\"All models loaded\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"4e10a17a-62af-4ecc-a675-d8b1b1899087","_cell_guid":"d39f749d-8e10-432c-abd0-e2265ce898e3","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 6. Training Curves\n\nThese plots show how the losses evolve during training. I track three components: classification loss (person vs. background), box regression loss, and the Re-ID loss (OIM or triplet). All values were logged by wandb during training; here I also reconstruct them from the saved loss logs for convenience.","metadata":{"_uuid":"8f0b5ee1-8bc6-4f39-aa9f-9775e09d8739","_cell_guid":"bde4f3cc-9050-4059-92d1-6845d0fec47f","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def plot_loss_curves(logs, keys=(\"loss_cls\", \"loss_box_reg\", \"loss_reid\")):\n    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, len(keys), figsize=(5 * len(keys), 4))\n    colors = {\"Baseline (R50+OIM)\": \"#4C72B0\",\n              \"Ablation A (R18+OIM)\": \"#DD8452\",\n              \"Ablation B (R50+Tri)\": \"#55A868\"}\n\n    for ax, key in zip(axes, keys):\n        for name, log in logs.items():\n            if not log:\n                continue\n            vals = [e.get(key, 0.0) for e in log]\n            ax.plot(range(1, len(vals) + 1), vals, label=name,\n                    color=colors.get(name), linewidth=2)\n        ax.set_title(key.replace(\"loss_\", \"Loss: \"))\n        ax.set_xlabel(\"Epoch\")\n        ax.legend(fontsize=8)\n        ax.grid(alpha=0.3)\n\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.savefig(\"training_curves.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n    plt.show()\n\nall_logs = {\n    \"Baseline (R50+OIM)\": log_baseline,\n    \"Ablation A (R18+OIM)\": log_resnet18,\n    \"Ablation B (R50+Tri)\": log_triplet,\n}\nplot_loss_curves(all_logs)","metadata":{"_uuid":"e7612e9d-9c8a-474a-89ca-8bbee65ccff9","_cell_guid":"fa7782a8-9bc8-4ab9-915c-f56f75d7f0bd","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 7. Feature Extraction\n\nTo evaluate, I need to:\n1. Run the detector on every test frame and collect detections + Re-ID embeddings (gallery).\n2. Extract an embedding for each of the 2,057 query crops.\n\nThen matching is done by cosine similarity between query and gallery embeddings.","metadata":{"_uuid":"15d2843e-ace0-417b-b43b-acf4998e64e9","_cell_guid":"06e45ade-07cf-4c4f-9bcf-95523db10fb8","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"eval_transform = T.Compose([T.ToTensor()])\n\ntest_ds_eval = PRWGalleryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, split=\"test\",\n                                  transform=eval_transform)\nquery_ds_eval = PRWQueryDataset(DATASET_ROOT, transform=eval_transform)\n\nprint(\"Extracting features for Baseline...\")\ngallery_dets_base, gallery_feats_base = extract_gallery_features(\n    model_baseline, test_ds_eval, DEVICE)\nquery_feats_base = extract_query_features(\n    model_baseline, query_ds_eval, DEVICE)\n\nprint(\"Extracting features for Ablation A...\")\ngallery_dets_r18, gallery_feats_r18 = extract_gallery_features(\n    model_resnet18, test_ds_eval, DEVICE)\nquery_feats_r18 = extract_query_features(\n    model_resnet18, query_ds_eval, DEVICE)\n\nprint(\"Extracting features for Ablation B...\")\ngallery_dets_tri, gallery_feats_tri = extract_gallery_features(\n    model_triplet, test_ds_eval, DEVICE)\nquery_feats_tri = extract_query_features(\n    model_triplet, query_ds_eval, DEVICE)\n\nprint(\"Feature extraction complete\")","metadata":{"_uuid":"84c72000-408d-4564-8ea6-d4c5eb4fdf6e","_cell_guid":"00cde330-a579-4304-973a-2386ebf49cf1","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 8. Quantitative Evaluation\n\nI use `eval_search_prw` (adapted from SeqNet, Li et al., 2022) as required by the assignment. A detection counts as a true positive only if IoU > 0.5 with the ground truth AND the identity is correct. `ignore_cam_id=True` following the literature convention (see FAQ).","metadata":{"_uuid":"9a52bbac-4f5a-4d0d-a1b4-3b4db979737a","_cell_guid":"5b162f27-c3f6-4d48-8a7a-63410d4d6213","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(\"[Baseline] ResNet-50 + OIM\")\nmAP_base, top1_base, aps_base = eval_search_prw(\n    test_ds_eval, query_ds_eval,\n    gallery_dets_base, gallery_feats_base, query_feats_base,\n    det_thresh=DET_THRESH)\n\nprint(\"\\n[Ablation A] ResNet-18 + OIM\")\nmAP_r18, top1_r18, aps_r18 = eval_search_prw(\n    test_ds_eval, query_ds_eval,\n    gallery_dets_r18, gallery_feats_r18, query_feats_r18,\n    det_thresh=DET_THRESH)\n\nprint(\"\\n[Ablation B] ResNet-50 + Triplet\")\nmAP_tri, top1_tri, aps_tri = eval_search_prw(\n    test_ds_eval, query_ds_eval,\n    gallery_dets_tri, gallery_feats_tri, query_feats_tri,\n    det_thresh=DET_THRESH)","metadata":{"_uuid":"3d460ecf-a820-48d1-9596-22f5f187eb19","_cell_guid":"0216367a-10bb-4bb5-ba66-5672a8e46cbb","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 9. Ablation Study\n\n### Hypotheses\n\n**Ablation A (backbone depth):**\nResNet-18 has fewer residual blocks than ResNet-50, which means less representational capacity at the deepest FPN level. I expect weaker features for both detection (lower recall) and re-identification (less discriminative embeddings), leading to lower mAP and top-1.\n\n**Ablation B (loss function):**\nOIM maintains a lookup table of all 482 training identity prototypes, so each embedding is compared against every known ID at every training step. Triplet loss only contrasts against IDs within the current mini-batch. With 2 images per GPU (4 effective), that is maybe 10-15 unique IDs per step at best. I expect OIM to outperform triplet, especially on mAP.","metadata":{"_uuid":"b037e88c-7ed6-4b5a-a3ed-6e45801065fc","_cell_guid":"656db7a0-c879-47e1-a6aa-e70091c421df","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# table\nprint(f\"{'Model':<30} {'Backbone':<12} {'Loss':<10} {'mAP':>8} {'Top-1':>8}\")\nprint(\"-\" * 70)\nfor name, bb, loss, m, t in [\n    (\"Baseline\", \"ResNet-50\", \"OIM\", mAP_base, top1_base),\n    (\"Ablation A\", \"ResNet-18\", \"OIM\", mAP_r18, top1_r18),\n    (\"Ablation B\", \"ResNet-50\", \"Triplet\", mAP_tri, top1_tri),\n]:\n    print(f\"{name:<30} {bb:<12} {loss:<10} {m*100:>7.1f}% {t*100:>7.1f}%\")\n\n# bar chart\nfig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(11, 4.5))\nlabels = [\"Baseline\\n(R50+OIM)\", \"Ablation A\\n(R18+OIM)\",\n          \"Ablation B\\n(R50+Triplet)\"]\ncolors = [\"#4C72B0\", \"#DD8452\", \"#55A868\"]\nmaps  = [mAP_base * 100, mAP_r18 * 100, mAP_tri * 100]\ntop1s = [top1_base * 100, top1_r18 * 100, top1_tri * 100]\n\nfor ax, vals, metric in zip(axes, [maps, top1s],\n                             [\"mAP (%)\", \"Top-1 Accuracy (%)\"]):\n    bars = ax.bar(labels, vals, color=colors, edgecolor=\"white\", width=0.5)\n    for bar, v in zip(bars, vals):\n        ax.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2, bar.get_height() + 0.3,\n                f\"{v:.1f}%\", ha=\"center\", va=\"bottom\", fontsize=11,\n                fontweight=\"bold\")\n    ax.set_title(metric, fontsize=13)\n    ax.set_ylim(0, max(vals) * 1.25)\n    ax.yaxis.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n    ax.set_axisbelow(True)\n\nplt.suptitle(\"Ablation Study: Person Search on PRW\", fontsize=13, y=1.02)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig(\"ablation_results.png\", dpi=130, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()","metadata":{"_uuid":"9ade794b-299a-42cc-9f3d-d18a765a4b27","_cell_guid":"fd3d2684-5b61-4a73-b8d1-5ba64d74d7af","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(14, 4))\nfor ax, (ap_arr, name, color) in zip(axes, [\n        (aps_base, \"Baseline (R50+OIM)\", \"#4C72B0\"),\n        (aps_r18,  \"Ablation A (R18+OIM)\", \"#DD8452\"),\n        (aps_tri,  \"Ablation B (R50+Tri)\", \"#55A868\"),\n    ]):\n    ax.hist(ap_arr, bins=30, color=color, edgecolor=\"white\", alpha=0.85)\n    ax.axvline(np.mean(ap_arr), color=\"red\", linestyle=\"--\",\n               linewidth=1.5, label=f\"mean={np.mean(ap_arr):.3f}\")\n    ax.set_title(name, fontsize=11)\n    ax.set_xlabel(\"AP per Query\")\n    ax.legend(fontsize=9)\n    ax.grid(alpha=0.3)\n\nplt.suptitle(\"Per-Query AP Distribution\", fontsize=13)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.savefig(\"ap_distribution.png\", dpi=120, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\nplt.show()","metadata":{"_uuid":"9bc647ee-c5b3-4ef6-88d1-3f269e74256b","_cell_guid":"9c5d8628-65fe-4e7d-a1db-9b0478652835","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Discussion\n\n**Ablation A (backbone):**\nResNet-18 shows a clear drop in both metrics. The shallower backbone produces weaker features at every FPN level since FPN relies on top-down propagation from the deepest stage. This hurts both detection (lower recall, missed persons especially at small scales) and re-identification (less discriminative embeddings, more confusion between similar-looking people). The AP distribution shifts uniformly leftward, so this is not limited to a few hard queries but is a broad effect.\n\n**Ablation B (loss):**\nThe triplet variant also falls behind OIM. The core issue is batch size. With 2 images per GPU, there are only a handful of unique IDs in each training step. The \"hardest negative\" in such a small pool is unlikely to be globally hard. OIM sidesteps this entirely because the LUT stores prototypes for all 482 IDs, updated via momentum. Every training step effectively contrasts against the full identity space. The circular queue adds further negatives from unlabeled pedestrians.\n\nThese results validate two design choices: (1) deeper backbones are worth the extra compute for this joint task, and (2) OIM is specifically suited for person search because it decouples the number of contrastive identities from the batch size.","metadata":{"_uuid":"1f91f97c-b203-4b20-a9f1-d23bfd9b46de","_cell_guid":"6e966c03-612c-4452-8de1-cd96c2c3037b","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 10. Qualitative Results\n\nBelow I show the top-5 gallery retrievals for several queries. Green borders = correct match (IoU >= 0.5, correct ID). Red = wrong.","metadata":{"_uuid":"5823bff4-635b-4694-85dc-a8278b7032e9","_cell_guid":"81bb2333-90e4-4e3b-9462-42ee69c6f051","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"def _compute_iou_np(a, b):\n    x1 = max(a[0], b[0]); y1 = max(a[1], b[1])\n    x2 = min(a[2], b[2]); y2 = min(a[3], b[3])\n    inter = max(0, x2 - x1) * max(0, y2 - y1)\n    union = (a[2]-a[0])*(a[3]-a[1]) + (b[2]-b[0])*(b[3]-b[1]) - inter\n    return inter / max(union, 1e-6)\n\n\ndef get_topk(gallery_ds, query_ds, g_dets, g_feats, q_feats,\n             qi, k=5, thr=0.5):\n    annos = gallery_ds.annotations\n    ndf = {}\n    for ann, det, feat in zip(annos, g_dets, g_feats):\n        s = det[:, 4].ravel()\n        idx = np.where(s >= thr)[0]\n        if len(idx) > 0:\n            ndf[ann[\"img_name\"]] = (det[idx], feat[idx])\n\n    fp = q_feats[qi].ravel()\n    qa = query_ds.annotations[qi]\n    qpid = qa[\"pids\"]\n    qim = qa[\"img_name\"]\n\n    gt_imgs = {x[\"img_name\"]: x[\"boxes\"][x[\"pids\"] == qpid]\n               for x in annos if qpid in x[\"pids\"] and x[\"img_name\"] != qim}\n\n    sa, ia, ra, la = [], [], [], []\n    for item in annos:\n        gn = item[\"img_name\"]\n        if gn == qim or gn not in ndf:\n            continue\n        det, fg = ndf[gn]\n        fg = fg.reshape(fg.shape[:2])\n        sim = fg.dot(fp).ravel()\n        for s, roi in zip(sim, det):\n            lbl = 0\n            if gn in gt_imgs:\n                gt = gt_imgs[gn].ravel()\n                w, h = gt[2] - gt[0], gt[3] - gt[1]\n                t = min(0.5, w * h / ((w + 10) * (h + 10)))\n                if _compute_iou_np(roi[:4], gt) >= t:\n                    lbl = 1\n            sa.append(s); ia.append(gn); ra.append(roi[:4]); la.append(lbl)\n\n    idx = np.argsort(sa)[::-1][:k]\n    return [(ia[i], ra[i], la[i], sa[i]) for i in idx]\n\n\ndef vis_results(qi, model_name, query_ds, gallery_ds,\n                g_dets, g_feats, q_feats, k=5):\n    topk = get_topk(gallery_ds, query_ds, g_dets, g_feats, q_feats, qi, k)\n    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, k + 1, figsize=(3 * (k + 1), 5))\n\n    qa = query_ds.annotations[qi]\n    qimg = Image.open(osp.join(query_ds.query_dir, qa[\"img_name\"])).convert(\"RGB\")\n    axes[0].imshow(qimg)\n    axes[0].set_title(f\"QUERY\\nPID {qa['pids']}\", fontsize=10,\n                      fontweight=\"bold\", color=\"#4C72B0\")\n    axes[0].axis(\"off\")\n\n    for rank, (ax, (gn, roi, ok, sc)) in enumerate(zip(axes[1:], topk), 1):\n        gimg = np.array(Image.open(\n            osp.join(gallery_ds.img_prefix, gn)).convert(\"RGB\"))\n        x1, y1, x2, y2 = [int(v) for v in roi]\n        pad = 20\n        crop = gimg[max(0,y1-pad):min(gimg.shape[0],y2+pad),\n                     max(0,x1-pad):min(gimg.shape[1],x2+pad)]\n        c = \"#2ca02c\" if ok else \"#d62728\"\n        ax.imshow(crop)\n        mark = \"CORRECT\" if ok else \"WRONG\"\n        ax.set_title(f\"Rank {rank}\\n{sc:.2f}\\n{mark}\", fontsize=9,\n                     color=c, fontweight=\"bold\")\n        for spine in ax.spines.values():\n            spine.set_edgecolor(c); spine.set_linewidth(3)\n        ax.axis(\"off\")\n\n    plt.suptitle(f\"{model_name} | Query #{qi} (PID {qa['pids']})\", fontsize=12)\n    plt.tight_layout()\n    plt.savefig(f\"qual_q{qi}_{model_name.replace(' ','_')}.png\",\n                dpi=110, bbox_inches=\"tight\")\n    plt.show()\n\n\n# show results for several queries\nfor qi in [0, 5, 20, 50]:\n    vis_results(qi, \"Baseline (R50+OIM)\", query_ds_eval, test_ds_eval,\n                gallery_dets_base, gallery_feats_base, query_feats_base)\n\n# side-by-side for one query\nprint(\"=== Query #5: Baseline vs. Triplet ===\")\nvis_results(5, \"Baseline (R50+OIM)\", query_ds_eval, test_ds_eval,\n            gallery_dets_base, gallery_feats_base, query_feats_base)\nvis_results(5, \"Ablation B (R50+Triplet)\", query_ds_eval, test_ds_eval,\n            gallery_dets_tri, gallery_feats_tri, query_feats_tri)","metadata":{"_uuid":"5b55ee62-8418-455c-bd1f-e5db75ee37e9","_cell_guid":"4f0406c5-166d-4389-a6b2-b52aefc685c3","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 11. Failure Analysis\n\nUnderstanding when the model fails is as important as knowing when it succeeds. I look at the queries with the lowest AP to identify common failure patterns.","metadata":{"_uuid":"81c76284-e39a-4db8-8f62-224bc9c24165","_cell_guid":"92bfaf6e-8cab-47d3-a360-26148e16b59d","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"sorted_idx = np.argsort(aps_base)\nworst_5 = sorted_idx[:5].tolist()\nbest_5  = sorted_idx[-5:][::-1].tolist()\n\nprint(\"5 Worst Queries (lowest AP):\")\nfor qi in worst_5:\n    ann = query_ds_eval.annotations[qi]\n    print(f\"  Query #{qi:4d}  PID={ann['pids']}  AP={aps_base[qi]:.3f}\")\n\nprint(\"\\n5 Best Queries (highest AP):\")\nfor qi in best_5:\n    ann = query_ds_eval.annotations[qi]\n    print(f\"  Query #{qi:4d}  PID={ann['pids']}  AP={aps_base[qi]:.3f}\")\n\nfor qi in worst_5[:2]:\n    vis_results(qi, \"Baseline [HARD]\", query_ds_eval, test_ds_eval,\n                gallery_dets_base, gallery_feats_base, query_feats_base)","metadata":{"_uuid":"f74662db-9248-4c6a-ae5a-49083a196a62","_cell_guid":"ac76170d-28a0-42ea-ba97-c6d0ba52cbb6","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 12. Conclusions\n\n### Summary of findings\n\n1. **End-to-end training works.** Sharing the backbone between detection and Re-ID lets the two tasks reinforce each other. The features adapt to be simultaneously good for localization and identity discrimination.\n\n2. **OIM is the right loss for this setting.** Its lookup table decouples the number of contrastive identities from the batch size, which is essential when GPU memory forces small batches. Triplet loss suffers from poor negative mining under these constraints.\n\n3. **Backbone depth matters.** ResNet-18 lacks the capacity to produce features rich enough for the joint task. The degradation affects both detection recall and Re-ID accuracy.\n\n4. **Hard cases.** The model struggles with heavy occlusion, very small persons, and clothing ambiguity (multiple people dressed similarly). These are fundamental challenges of the dataset.\n\n### Possible improvements\n\n- Stronger backbones (ResNet-101, Swin Transformer) for richer features.\n- Random Erasing augmentation (Zhong et al., AAAI 2020) for occlusion robustness.\n- CBGM post-processing (Context Bipartite Graph Matching) for spatial co-occurrence.\n- Gradient accumulation to further increase effective batch size.\n\n### DDP experience\n\nUsing DistributedDataParallel on Kaggle's 2x T4 setup roughly halved training time compared to a single GPU. The main consideration is ensuring the sampler is reseeded each epoch and that only rank 0 handles I/O (logging, saving, wandb). For larger-scale experiments, this would scale naturally to more GPUs.","metadata":{"_uuid":"92d29bc4-978a-404e-8a70-429b147c87aa","_cell_guid":"1f4b5359-b9c0-4bed-abfb-a6d29ed62f63","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## References\n\n1. Zheng et al. \"Person Re-identification in the Wild\". CVPR 2017.\n2. Xiao et al. \"Joint Detection and Identification Feature Learning for Person Search\". CVPR 2017.\n3. Li et al. \"SeqNet: Learning Descriptors for Sequence-Based Hierarchical Place Recognition\". RA-L 2022. (eval function adapted from their repo)\n4. Jaffe et al. \"Gallery Filter Network for Person Search\". WACV 2023.\n5. Yu et al. \"Cascade Transformers for End-to-End Person Search\". CVPR 2022.\n6. Hermans et al. \"In Defense of the Triplet Loss for Person Re-Identification\". arXiv 2017.\n7. Zhong et al. \"Random Erasing Data Augmentation\". AAAI 2020.","metadata":{"_uuid":"3b79f741-6799-4234-ace5-7b874c2374b7","_cell_guid":"9441a587-c1cb-43b4-89af-b73ec330d6c5","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"","metadata":{"_uuid":"95090189-15e8-4ded-97dd-835489984ff2","_cell_guid":"c2d525ad-3568-4a33-bc42-af0bfa2e6209","trusted":true,"collapsed":false,"jupyter":{"outputs_hidden":false}}}]}